00:00:22.860 --> 00:00:24.631
PROFESSOR: So first
up, we're going

00:00:24.631 --> 00:00:26.130
to go around, do a
couple of things.

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:27.430
We'll just go in pairs.

00:00:27.430 --> 00:00:31.910
We'll try these out, so
you two can come up first.

00:00:31.910 --> 00:00:34.860
We'll start off with one
of our basic principles

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:43.010
of electromagnetism, which
is that we can spin metal

00:00:43.010 --> 00:00:48.010
in a magnetic field
and produce current.

00:00:48.010 --> 00:00:53.730
So let's hook up our
little motor to an LED

00:00:53.730 --> 00:00:59.910
and see if we can make
our motor into a dynamo.

00:00:59.910 --> 00:01:01.418
OK, so it works.

00:01:01.418 --> 00:01:02.679
It's not easy, but it works.

00:01:02.679 --> 00:01:04.220
We're using a motor
in reverse, we're

00:01:04.220 --> 00:01:05.920
spinning metal in
a magnetic field

00:01:05.920 --> 00:01:09.130
and producing some current
to light up our LED.

00:01:09.130 --> 00:01:11.290
There we go.

00:01:11.290 --> 00:01:15.630
Now, let's plug in this
to our amplifiers and

00:01:15.630 --> 00:01:19.630
try to re-do our
telharmonium light.

00:01:19.630 --> 00:01:22.450
So it's the turn of the century.

00:01:22.450 --> 00:01:24.380
It's around 1900.

00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:27.615
You're Cahill, and you're like
I need a way to produce sound.

00:01:27.615 --> 00:01:29.240
I need the way to
create an oscillator.

00:01:29.240 --> 00:01:30.115
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:31.235 --> 00:01:32.610
PROFESSOR: Who
would have thought

00:01:32.610 --> 00:01:34.151
that this is the
best way to do this.

00:01:41.970 --> 00:01:43.720
STUDENT: That's what
my dad's [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:46.424 --> 00:01:48.007
PROFESSOR: We need
definitely some way

00:01:48.007 --> 00:01:49.930
to spin this faster
so we can get a tone.

00:01:49.930 --> 00:01:52.986
But you can hear that if it were
spinning at some constant rate

00:01:52.986 --> 00:01:53.870
you could get--

00:01:53.870 --> 00:01:55.542
STUDENT: This motor
has less resistance

00:01:55.542 --> 00:01:57.466
so it continues to get a tone.

00:01:57.466 --> 00:01:59.773
That motor's tighter,
but so you just--

00:01:59.773 --> 00:02:01.314
STUDENT: It's got
a better motor now.

00:02:06.507 --> 00:02:07.090
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:02:07.090 --> 00:02:08.410
Can it work as a
musical instrument?

00:02:08.410 --> 00:02:09.345
STUDENT: Sure, whatever.

00:02:09.345 --> 00:02:10.860
PROFESSOR: What
would we need to do?

00:02:10.860 --> 00:02:11.740
If you wanted it to make a--

00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:13.531
STUDENT: You need two
interfaces, for sure.

00:02:13.531 --> 00:02:14.790
PROFESSOR: Two parameters.

00:02:14.790 --> 00:02:16.590
STUDENT: Maybe if
I twiddle those--

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:18.860
STUDENT: I got all these
parameters right here.

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:21.837
STUDENT: Add volume
with the turntables.

00:02:21.837 --> 00:02:22.420
STUDENT: Yeah.

00:02:22.420 --> 00:02:22.915
STUDENT: Oh yeah.

00:02:22.915 --> 00:02:23.456
Sounds great.

00:02:28.855 --> 00:02:32.815
STUDENT: And you could light
it up at the same time.

00:02:32.815 --> 00:02:35.106
PROFESSOR: OK, next up.

00:02:35.106 --> 00:02:35.880
OK, good.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:37.870
So next up.

00:02:37.870 --> 00:02:39.278
STUDENT: Which one do you want?

00:02:39.278 --> 00:02:41.108
PROFESSOR: OK, so you
guys gotta work as a team.

00:02:41.108 --> 00:02:43.316
Do you want to try the motor
while they're connected?

00:02:43.316 --> 00:02:44.970
Actually, just feel
the motor so you

00:02:44.970 --> 00:02:47.913
can get a little sense of how--

00:02:47.913 --> 00:02:49.038
STUDENT: It is really hard.

00:02:49.038 --> 00:02:49.758
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:02:49.758 --> 00:02:51.966
PROFESSOR: Try the quick
flick you get a little bit--

00:02:55.382 --> 00:02:56.537
STUDENT: OK, I'm done.

00:02:56.537 --> 00:02:57.370
PROFESSOR: OK, good.

00:02:57.370 --> 00:02:59.840
So here is our humbucker.

00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:02.070
Two signal coils
next to each other.

00:03:02.070 --> 00:03:06.260
Essentially, just a big wrath
of wire with some little

00:03:06.260 --> 00:03:08.550
poles to focus the
magnetic energy.

00:03:08.550 --> 00:03:11.310
Now, this design, this
a nice DeMarzio pickup.

00:03:11.310 --> 00:03:13.440
I was talking
earlier, it's in pink.

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:15.270
I got the pink one
because it was cheaper.

00:03:15.270 --> 00:03:17.976
Think about the issues
involved in that.

00:03:17.976 --> 00:03:21.400
The pink pickup is cheaper than
a black one, same performance.

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:24.790
Anyways, this model
has four conductors

00:03:24.790 --> 00:03:27.720
which allows us to access
each of the coils separately.

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:30.500
We're going to
run them in series

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:32.670
and treat them
just as one pickup.

00:03:32.670 --> 00:03:38.630
So we need our--
this is our ground ,

00:03:38.630 --> 00:03:41.092
here and this is our
hot signal, the red.

00:03:41.092 --> 00:03:43.050
STUDENT: Does that mean
that you're essentially

00:03:43.050 --> 00:03:46.170
eliminating any benefits of
the reverse polarity humbucking

00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:46.670
action?

00:03:46.670 --> 00:03:48.961
PROFESSOR: The humbucking
action works into both series

00:03:48.961 --> 00:03:53.017
and parallel, according to
the DeMarzio literature.

00:03:53.017 --> 00:03:54.600
STUDENT: It seems
like if you ran them

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:56.780
in series that
reversing them again,

00:03:56.780 --> 00:03:59.925
you would just knock out
the sequel altogether.

00:03:59.925 --> 00:04:00.508
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:04:00.508 --> 00:04:01.216
So you got it in?

00:04:01.216 --> 00:04:06.120
Now, the first thing to
try is turning our motor--

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:09.240
before we get to the phone.

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:11.480
Now, what this
device is going to do

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:16.860
is pick up moving metal that
perturbs the magnetic field.

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:19.079
So if we spin our motor
in front of the pickup,

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:20.412
let's see if we can get a sound.

00:04:28.424 --> 00:04:29.410
There we go, OK?

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:32.311
STUDENT: It's the same sound.

00:04:32.311 --> 00:04:34.746
PROFESSOR: It's the same
sound, that's right.

00:04:34.746 --> 00:04:38.630
Which shouldn't be
surprising, but it is still.

00:04:38.630 --> 00:04:39.420
OK, good.

00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:44.230
Now, what if we put a vibrating
metal string on top of this?

00:04:44.230 --> 00:04:47.650
Maybe we might pick
up a sound, right?

00:04:47.650 --> 00:04:51.150
Let's try it on piano.

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:54.880
OK, so one of you can play
the keys here and hold down

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:56.308
the damper.

00:04:56.308 --> 00:05:01.475
And the other needs to--

00:05:01.475 --> 00:05:02.282
STUDENT: Feedback?

00:05:02.282 --> 00:05:04.198
PROFESSOR: Yeah, you're
going to get feedback.

00:05:18.152 --> 00:05:19.610
STUDENT: Try to go
for a lower one.

00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:21.568
PROFESSOR: It has a high
directionality action.

00:05:21.568 --> 00:05:23.604
STUDENT: Maybe if we
do a really quiet note.

00:05:23.604 --> 00:05:25.603
PROFESSOR: So it really
matters is the location.

00:05:32.576 --> 00:05:33.076
There we go.

00:05:36.429 --> 00:05:38.534
Maybe turn off the distortion.

00:05:38.534 --> 00:05:39.200
STUDENT: Oh, OK.

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:40.033
PROFESSOR: Yeah, OK.

00:05:40.033 --> 00:05:40.605
Try it again.

00:05:45.300 --> 00:05:46.800
Now just move it--
hold on one note.

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:48.720
Press that one note
repeatedly and move the pickup

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:50.219
to the left and
right so we can hear

00:05:50.219 --> 00:05:54.028
how focused the
pickup is on that.

00:05:54.028 --> 00:05:55.153
This is pretty interesting.

00:05:59.630 --> 00:06:04.595
Now, if you actually
rest it on the keys.

00:06:04.595 --> 00:06:07.565
Now we have to prepare the
electromagnetic feedback.

00:06:10.535 --> 00:06:15.950
Now, we could try to do
some sort of ebo thing

00:06:15.950 --> 00:06:18.240
where we direct the
acoustic energy out

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:22.016
of the pickup on the strings.

00:06:22.016 --> 00:06:23.140
STUDENT: Out of the pickup?

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:25.260
PROFESSOR: Out of the
amp onto the strings.

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:26.150
STUDENT: Oh.

00:06:26.150 --> 00:06:26.515
STUDENT: All right.

00:06:26.515 --> 00:06:27.550
PROFESSOR: Now, this
isn't going to work great,

00:06:27.550 --> 00:06:30.160
but the idea here is that
we're using the amplification

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:34.110
to re-resonate the
string and creating

00:06:34.110 --> 00:06:36.335
a feedback loop in the process.

00:06:36.335 --> 00:06:37.710
STUDENT: Want me
to start it off?

00:06:37.710 --> 00:06:40.110
STUDENT: Ah, yes.

00:06:40.110 --> 00:06:43.420
PROFESSOR: Hold down
the damper, too.

00:06:43.420 --> 00:06:45.260
And actually, if you
rest it on the keys,

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:53.750
you're probably going--
The damper's way up.

00:06:56.660 --> 00:06:58.600
STUDENT: Yeah.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:06:59.178
Nice.

00:06:59.178 --> 00:07:00.636
PROFESSOR: Now,
change the position

00:07:00.636 --> 00:07:01.938
of the speaker a little bit.

00:07:01.938 --> 00:07:02.936
See if you can--

00:07:09.922 --> 00:07:11.918
STUDENT: Yeah.

00:07:11.918 --> 00:07:15.284
STUDENT: I wish I had
an expensive piano.

00:07:15.284 --> 00:07:16.159
PROFESSOR: OK, great.

00:07:16.159 --> 00:07:16.409
Good.

00:07:16.409 --> 00:07:16.910
OK, guys.

00:07:16.910 --> 00:07:17.590
Good job.

00:07:17.590 --> 00:07:18.804
Who do we want.

00:07:18.804 --> 00:07:20.160
Next up.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.890
Leave the pickup
connected and now we

00:07:23.890 --> 00:07:27.097
need some sort of
devices that give off

00:07:27.097 --> 00:07:28.180
electromagnetic radiation.

00:07:28.180 --> 00:07:32.464
Does anybody have a device
that gives off some radiation?

